f=Shared OS/logical/berger-contagious.md · in=Jonah Berger's *Contagious: Things Catch On* (2013) empirical answer question marketer asks: ideas spread while others die? Berger, Wharton marketing professor, analyzed thousands New York Times most-emailed articles, products, viral content identify six shared principles. named them STEPPS: Social Currency, Triggers, Emotion, Public, Practical Value, Stories. Berger's framework extends Cialdini's persuasion principles interpersonal social Cialdini explains individual says yes; Berger explains crowd shares. Together they form complete contagion architecture. · h2:THE BERGER-CIALDINI CONNECTION=Berger's STEPPS map directly onto Cialdini's six principles: · h2:THE BERGER-CIALDINI CONNECTION=\| Berger (Sharing) \| Cialdini (Persuasion) \| Mechanism \| · h2:THE BERGER-CIALDINI CONNECTION=\|------------------\|----------------------\|-----------\| · h2:THE BERGER-CIALDINI CONNECTION=\| Social Currency \| Liking \| People want to look good → share things that make them look good \| · h2:THE BERGER-CIALDINI CONNECTION=\| Triggers \| Commitment/Consistency \| Repeated exposure → top-of-mind → action (Mere Exposure + Consistency) \| · h2:THE BERGER-CIALDINI CONNECTION=\| Emotion \| Reciprocity \| High-arousal emotion triggers reciprocal engagement \| · h2:THE BERGER-CIALDINI CONNECTION=\| Public \| Social Proof \| Observable behavior → imitation cascade \| · h2:THE BERGER-CIALDINI CONNECTION=\| Practical Value \| Reciprocity \| Giving useful information → reciprocity debt → engagement \| · h2:THE BERGER-CIALDINI CONNECTION=\| Stories \| Liking + Authority \| Stories humanize (Liking) and carry evidence (Authority) \|